Just inside the forest about 15ft up in a tree.  Amplified and high pass filter with Audacity.

Sitting on a dead tree limb as expected for this species.  The woods were quiet except for the the pee-yur call of the Pewee.  My observation is that post-breeding this is the vocalization our might expect to hear instead of the full song.  This is a weak recording.  the bird was fairly distant for the microphone.

recordings.loc: Bald Mountain Park, South RA, Oakland County, MI

recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Call at e.g., 0:01, 0:10, and 0:24. Bird foraging in a tulip poplar and surrounding trees ~5-7m above the ground. Sallying from a branch to capture insects in the air, sometimes returning to the same perch, sometimes perching on a new branch. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.rmk: I heard this flycatcher yesterday in the trees near Lake Jesup.  I did not see the bird, since it was in an area of the park that is not accessible. At first I thought it was an Eastern Wood-Pewee.  Then I through it might be short enough of a call to be a Yellow-bellied Flycatcher.  I'm still leaning towards a Pewee, since that species is very common in the park this time of year.

heard at the clearing of Canande Lodge.  The focus sound is the drawn out call increasing in pitch that is repeated throughout the recording. It presumably comes from a small brown-grey flycatcher/tyrannulet that was observed at the time.
The whistled call. Some sort of flycatcher has been suggested
